    {
      "question": "During a tax audit examination, revenue agent Lisa Chen requested access to the taxpayer's electronic accounting records stored on a company laptop. The taxpayer's representative, Mark Sullivan, refused to provide the password, citing Fifth Amendment protection against self-incrimination. The company's attorney argued that compelling the password disclosure would violate the taxpayer's constitutional rights. How should Lisa proceed, and what are the taxpayer's rights regarding electronic records access during an IRS examination?",
      "answer": "Lisa should recognize that while taxpayers have certain constitutional protections, the Fifth Amendment privilege against self-incrimination has limitations in the context of business records. The 'required records doctrine' generally requires taxpayers to maintain and produce business records even if they contain incriminating information, as these records are regulatory in nature. However, the act of producing documents or providing passwords may receive Fifth Amendment protection under the 'act of production doctrine' if the act itself is testimonial and incriminating.\n\nLisa should:\n1) Explain that business records are generally not protected by the Fifth Amendment under the required records exception\n2) Consider whether a summons is needed to compel production\n3) Consult with IRS Counsel if the taxpayer continues to assert Fifth Amendment privileges\n4) Document the refusal and the grounds asserted\n5) Consider alternative methods of obtaining the information\n\nThe taxpayer has the right to:\n- Assert constitutional protections where applicable\n- Have reasonable time to consult with counsel\n- Receive proper summons procedures if informal requests are refused\n- Challenge summons enforcement in court\n- Have the examination conducted at reasonable times and places\n\nThe password issue specifically may involve both Fourth Amendment (privacy) and Fifth Amendment (testimonial aspect of providing the password) considerations that may require legal review before compulsion.",
      "topic": "S2D07",
      "sub_topic": "Constitutional Protections During Examinations",
      "num": 3
    },
    {
      "question": "During a tax examination, the IRS revenue agent requests that the taxpayer's CPA provide all working papers related to the tax return under examination. The CPA is concerned about the taxpayer's rights during this process. Which of the following statements is TRUE regarding the taxpayer's rights during an IRS examination?",
      "options": [
        "The taxpayer has the right to refuse the examination entirely if they believe it is without merit",
        "The taxpayer has the right to have the examination conducted at a reasonable time and place that is convenient for both parties",
        "The taxpayer must provide all requested documents within 10 days or face automatic penalties",
        "The taxpayer has no right to representation during the examination phase, only during appeals"
      ],
      "correct_answer": "The taxpayer has the right to have the examination conducted at a reasonable time and place that is convenient for both parties",
      "explanation": "Under the Taxpayer Bill of Rights, specifically the right to a fair and just tax system, taxpayers have the right to have examinations conducted at reasonable times and places. IRS Policy Statement 4-3 requires that examinations be conducted at times and places convenient to both the taxpayer and the IRS. Taxpayers cannot refuse examinations entirely (option A), there is no automatic 10-day deadline with automatic penalties (option C), and taxpayers have the right to representation at any point during an examination (option D).",
      "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations",
      "subtopic": "Examination Procedures and Taxpayer Rights",
      "num": 4
