    {
      "question": "During a tax examination, Revenue Agent Thompson requests to interview Sarah Mitchell, the CFO of XYZ Corporation, regarding potential income underreporting. Sarah asks whether she has the right to have her attorney present during the interview. Which of the following statements is CORRECT regarding Sarah's rights during this examination?\n\nA. Sarah must submit a written request to the IRS at least 10 days before the interview to have representation present.\n\nB. Sarah has the right to have her attorney, CPA, or enrolled agent present during the interview, and the IRS cannot deny this right.\n\nC. Sarah can only have representation present if she is personally under criminal investigation.\n\nD. The Revenue Agent has discretion to allow or deny representation during administrative interviews.",
      "answer": "B",
      "explanation": "Under IRC Section 7521(c) and Treasury Regulation 301.7521-1, taxpayers have an absolute right to be represented during any interview with the IRS concerning the determination or collection of tax. This right applies to both individual and corporate taxpayers, and the IRS cannot condition or deny this right. The taxpayer may be represented by an attorney, CPA, enrolled agent, or other person authorized to practice before the IRS. Option A is incorrect because no advance written request is required. Option C is incorrect because the right to representation applies to all examinations, not just criminal investigations. Option D is incorrect because the IRS has no discretion to deny this right.",
      "source": "IRC Section 7521(c); Treas. Reg. 301.7521-1",
      "num": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "S2D07-Q6",
      "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations",
      "question": "During a tax examination, the IRS revenue agent requests to interview a taxpayer's bookkeeper without the taxpayer or their representative present. The taxpayer's CPA objects, stating that all interviews must be conducted with the representative present. What are the taxpayer's rights regarding witness interviews during an examination, and what procedures should the revenue agent follow?",
      "answer": "Under IRC §7602, the IRS has the authority to examine books and records and to summon witnesses during an examination. However, taxpayers have specific rights regarding witness interviews:\n\n1. **Right to representation**: While the taxpayer has the right to be represented during the examination, third-party witnesses (like the bookkeeper) may be interviewed separately without the taxpayer or representative present.\n\n2. **Summons authority**: The IRS can issue a summons under IRC §7602 to compel testimony from third parties, including employees, without requiring the taxpayer's presence.\n\n3. **Voluntary vs. compelled interviews**: If the interview is voluntary, the bookkeeper can choose whether to have the taxpayer's representative present. If summoned, the witness must appear as directed.\n\n4. **Taxpayer notification**: Generally, the IRS should provide reasonable notice to the taxpayer when seeking to interview employees or third parties.\n\n5. **Representative's role**: The CPA cannot prevent the IRS from interviewing third-party witnesses, but can advise their client and the witnesses of their rights.\n\nThe revenue agent should explain these rights, proceed with the interview if legally authorized, and document the process appropriately. The taxpayer can instruct employees regarding cooperation but cannot obstruct legitimate IRS interviews.",
      "num": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "S2D07-Q7",
      "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations",
      "question": "During a CRA tax audit examination, the auditor requests access to a taxpayer's personal computer and smartphone to review business-related communications and records. The taxpayer is concerned about privacy rights regarding personal information unrelated to their business. What are the taxpayer's rights regarding scope limitations on CRA examination powers, and what steps can the taxpayer take to protect personal information while still complying with the CRA's lawful examination authority under the Income Tax Act?",
      "answer": "Under the Income Tax Act, the CRA has broad examination powers under sections 231.1 and 231.2, but these powers are not unlimited and must respect the taxpayer's privacy rights:\n\n**Scope of CRA Examination Powers:**\n- The CRA can examine records, processes, and property relevant to tax compliance\n- Examination powers must be exercised for a proper purpose related to tax administration\n- The powers are limited to information reasonably required to verify compliance\n\n**Taxpayer Privacy Rights:**\n- Charter protection against unreasonable search and seizure (section 8)\n- Right to privacy regarding personal information unrelated to tax matters\n- Solicitor-client privilege protection for legal communications\n- Accountant-client privilege in Quebec for professional communications\n\n**Steps the Taxpayer Can Take:**\n1. Request clarification on the specific information being sought and its relevance\n2. Offer to provide only business-related records in segregated format\n3. Propose reviewing the devices themselves and extracting only relevant business communications\n4. Create copies with only business-related information, certified as complete\n5. Request that examination occur in presence of representative\n6. Object formally if requests exceed lawful scope\n7. Seek judicial review if CRA issues requirement or demand believed to be overly broad\n8. Consider applying for judicial authorization review under section 231.2(3)\n\n**Best Practices:**\n- Maintain separate devices/accounts for business and personal use\n- Keep business records organized and segregated\n- Document all communications with CRA regarding scope\n- Seek professional advice before granting access to personal devices\n- Cooperate with reasonable requests while protecting irrelevant personal information",
      "num": 7
    }
  ]
